# Telegram Agent Daemon

The daemon lives in `tools/telegram-agent/` and runs 24/7 on the local PC via PM2. It is a **standalone Node.js package** — it is NOT part of the pnpm workspace or turborepo. Do not add it to `pnpm-workspace.yaml`.

## File layout

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `src/index.ts` | Bot init, whitelist guard, start long-polling |
| `src/router.ts` | Routes messages: memory → fantasy → devops → code |
| `src/memory.ts` | Read/write `memory/agent-memory.md`, inject into Claude calls |
| `src/approval.ts` | Inline keyboard approval gate, git commit+push on approve |
| `src/handlers/fantasy.ts` | Slash commands that call `/internal/agents/run` on Render |
| `src/handlers/devops.ts` | Render/GitHub API calls for /status /logs /deploy /prs |
| `src/handlers/code.ts` | Free-form coding tasks via Claude Sonnet + local filesystem |

## Memory file

`tools/telegram-agent/memory/agent-memory.md` is **user-owned personal data**.
- It is gitignored — **never commit it, never overwrite it in code edits**
- When editing the daemon source, do not touch or reference specific content in this file
- It is read and updated at runtime only

## API changes

Fantasy commands use `POST /internal/agents/run` + `GET /internal/agents/:id` in `apps/api/src/routes/internal.ts`.
- Both endpoints use `adminGuard` (accepts `x-admin-secret` header)
- All 7 agent types are supported by the POST endpoint
- Do not change the auth model on these routes

## Coding constraints

- The daemon uses ESM (`"type": "module"`) with `tsx` as the runtime
- Use `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` + `dirname()` for `__dirname` equivalents (Node 20 compatible)
- All env vars are loaded from the workspace root `.env` at startup
- `WORKSPACE_PATH` env var or auto-detected path (two dirs above `src/`) is the git repo root for file reads/writes
- Do not hardcode any league IDs, user IDs, or personal preferences — those live in `agent-memory.md`

## Response style rules

When the daemon replies on Telegram:
- Keep responses short and mobile-friendly (aim for < 800 chars per message)
- Use `*bold*` sparingly, no nested markdown
- Split messages > 4000 chars into multiple sends (Telegram limit)
- Never auto-commit or auto-push — always go through the approval gate

## Approval gate contract

`sendForApproval()` in `src/approval.ts` stores pending changes keyed by `chatId`.
- Only one pending approval per chat at a time
- `handleCallbackQuery` handles `approve` / `discard` callback data
- On approve: writes files → `git add .` → `git commit` → `git push`
- On discard: clears pending state, no file writes

## PM2 management

```bash
cd tools/telegram-agent
npm run pm2:start      # start daemon
npm run pm2:restart    # restart after code changes
npm run pm2:logs       # stream logs
npm run pm2:save       # persist + register Windows startup
```
